ference>ES/H009078/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The project studies the role(s) of accounting in the control of worker cooperatives from an anthropological perspective. It aims:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>To build connections between accounting and anthropology through an interdisciplinary seminar series, thereby developing a critical theorisation of organisational control as a conflictive process of subjectivity and objectivity;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To support the current revival of interest in cooperatives seen as elements of the globally emerging institutional sphere of the 'social economy'. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>Its methodology is to build on an interdisciplinary framework to analyse how accounting affects the management and subjective perceptions of the labour process as a material and value-creating process. Based on original material from eight ethnographic case studies of the empresas recuperadas (ERs)&amp;nbsp;- cooperatives established during Argentina's 2001 socio-economic crisis&amp;nbsp;- the framework allows an exploration of divergent processes of class formation, conceived as 'capital-centred' and 'worker-centred' forms of socialisation. Through a focus on social actors? use of accounting to redefine the possibilities of 'corporate social responsibility', the project explores whether cooperatives can contain new elements and are capable of reshaping the limits of the prevailing system even as they reproduce its contradictions. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>73730</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/H009078/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5E9AA4EC-49E3-4D6A-B545-79DA07CE39E0</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Management &amp; Business Studies</gtr:text></